<Layout 
  title="The Builder Â· Single-Point Accountability for Systems"
  description="Why one accountable builder produces better systems than agencies or rotating freelancers. Founder-built execution with long-term responsibility."
>
  <section style="padding: 80px 24px; max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto;">
    <h1 style="font-size: 2.5rem; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 24px;">The Builder</h1>
    <p style="font-size: 1.5rem; color: #b0b0c0; line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 48px;">
      Single-point accountability for systems that matter.
    </p>

    <div style="background: #1a1a23; border: 1px solid #2a2a35; border-radius: 8px; padding: 48px; margin-bottom: 48px;">
      <h2 style="font-size: 1.8rem; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 24px; color: #f0f0f5;">Why One Builder Beats an Agency</h2>
      <p style="color: #b0b0c0; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 24px;">
        Agencies optimize for billable hours and smooth hand-offs. They delegate, they rotate teams, they create documentation for the next person. This works for marketing sites, but fails for internal systems that need to work daily.
      </p>
      <p style="color: #b0b0c0; line-height: 1.7;">
        One accountable builder means: <strong>no knowledge loss</strong>, <strong>no responsibility diffusion</strong>, <strong>no excuses</strong>. When something breaks, there's exactly one person who understands it completely and fixes it.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div style="background: #1a1a23; border: 1px solid #2a2a35; border-radius: 8px; padding: 48px; margin-bottom: 48px;">
      <h2 style="font-size: 1.8rem; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 24px; color: #f0f0f5;">The Accountability Difference</h2>
      <ul style="color: #b0b0c0; line-height: 1.7; padding-left: 24px;">
        <li style="margin-bottom: 16px;"><strong>No hand-offs:</strong> The person who architects also builds, also deploys, also maintains.</li>
        <li style="margin-bottom: 16px;"><strong>Long-term thinking:</strong> Building for maintainability because I'll be the one maintaining it.</li>
        <li style="margin-bottom: 16px;"><strong>Direct communication:</strong> No account managers, no project managers, no layers.</li>
        <li><strong>Skin in the game:</strong> My reputation depends on your system working, not just being delivered.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div style="background: #1a1a23; border: 1px solid #2a2a35; border-radius: 8px; padding: 48px;">
      <h2 style="font-size: 1.8rem; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 24px; color: #f0f0f5;">What "Founder-Built" Actually Means</h2>
      <p style="color: #b0b0c0; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 24px;">
        It doesn't mean I only work with founders (though I often do). It means I build systems with the same ownership mindset a founder has for their business.
      </p>
      <p style="color: #b0b0c0; line-height: 1.7;">
        I treat your system like it's my own: caring about the details, anticipating problems, and committing to its long-term success. This is the opposite of contractor mentality.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div style="text-align: center; margin-top: 64px;">
      <a href="/contact" style="background: #3a8bba; color: white; padding: 16px 32px; border-radius: 4px; text-decoration: none; font-weight: 600; font-size: 1.1rem; display: inline-block;">Describe Your Challenge</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
